	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The MMC1 does have mirroring control, so yeah, the games can select mirroring dynamically.
<br />
<br />I don't know if all carts that don't have pads have software mirroring control, but I'm pretty sure 99% of the time this is the case.
<br />
<br />Are you trying to make a repro of a game? If so I guess you might be confused about the mirroring defined on the iNES header, is that it? Well, for mappers that have mirroring control that information has no meaning at all. Don't worry about it.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Thu Feb 11, 2010 7:50 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">pivotman wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Do all cart that don't have pads change there mirroring at will?</div><br />Yes. Even some that do have pads, such as <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/TFROM" class="postlink">TFROM</a>, have three sets of pads: "force vertical arrangement", "force horizontal arrangement", and "mapper controlled".<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">What about an mmc1?</div>
<br />MMC1 is more flexible than a standard MMC3 in mirroring: it can freely switch among vertical mirroring, horizontal mirroring, and AOROM-style single screen mirroring. MMC3 lacks the single screen mode except on boards wired in a <a href="http://wiki.nesdev.com/w/index.php/INES_Mapper_118" class="postlink">configuration like TLSROM</a>, where the upper CHR ROM bank bit controls mirroring.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


